{{Orphan|date=January 2017}} {{Use American English|date=July 2018}} {{Use mdy dates|date=July 2018}} {{Cleanup infobox}} {{Infobox U.S. Courts of Appeals case |Litigants=Backun v. United States |Court=[[United States Court of Appeals for the Fourth Circuit]] |CourtSeal= |ArgueDate= |ArgueYear= |DecideDate=June 10, |DecideYear=1940 |FullName=Backun v. United States |Citations=112 [[F.2d]] [https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/F2/112/635/1498899/ 635] |Prior= |Subsequent= |Holding= |Judges=[[John J. Parker]], [[Morris Ames Soper]], [[Armistead Mason Dobie]] |Majority=Parker |JoinMajority=Dobie |Concurrence=Soper |LawsApplied= }} '''''Backun v. United States''''', 112 F.2d 635 (4th Cir. 1940),<ref>{{cite court |litigants=Backun v. United States |vol=112 |reporter=F.2d |opinion=635 |pinpoint= |court=[[4th Cir.]] |date=1940 |url=https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/F2/112/635/1498899/ |accessdate=2018-06-04 |quote=}}{{Usgovpd}}</ref> is a [[criminal case]] that held that the mental element for [[complicity]] in a crime is that the accessory had knowledge that aiding or abetting would facilitate the criminal act of the principal, and did not require the accomplice have the same purpose as the principal.<ref name=CL>[[John Kaplan (law professor)|John Kaplan]], [[Robert Weisberg]], Guyora Binder, ''Criminal Law - Cases and Materials'', 7th ed. 2012, [[Wolters Kluwer Law & Business]], page 761. {{ISBN|978-1-4548-0698-1}}</ref> The case is contrasted with ''[[United States v. Peoni]]'', which held the opposite.<ref name=CL/>
