'''Charles Pierre Henri Rieu''' (June 8, 1820 &ndash; March 19, 1902) was a Swiss [[oriental studies|Orientalist]], for many years Professor of [[Arabic language|Arabic]] in [[University College London|London]] and [[University of Cambridge|Cambridge]].
==Biography== Rieu was born at [[Geneva]], and studied at [[Bonn University]], where he received his doctors degree in 1843. He entered the [[British Museum]] in 1847, and after twenty years of service, a new post, that of Keeper of Oriental Manuscripts, was created for him.
He was a Professor of [[Arabic language|Arabic]] and [[Persian language|Persian]] at [[University College London]].<ref name=TTObituary /> In 1895 he was made professor of [[Arabic language|Arabic]] in the [[University of Cambridge]], with the full title '[[Sir Thomas Adams Professor of Arabic]]', in succession to [[William Robertson Smith|Robertson Smith]].<ref>{{acad|id=R894CP|name=Rieu, Charle Pierre Henri}}</ref>
Rieu died in [[London]] on 19 March 1902.<ref name=TTObituary>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Obituary |day_of_week=Friday |date=21 March 1902 |page_number=3 |issue=36721| }}</ref> He was the father of [[E. V. Rieu]].
==Publications== Rieu completed in 1871 the second part, dealing with Arabic manuscripts, of the ''Catalogus codicum manuscriptorum orientalium'', which had been begun by [[William Cureton]], and he issued a supplementary volume in 1894.
He also drew up a ''Catalogue of the Turkish Manuscripts'' (1888) and a ''Catalogue of the Persian Manuscripts'' (4 vols, 1879–95),<ref>[https://archive.org/details/catalogueofpersi01brituoft Catalogue of the Persian manuscripts in the British museum (1879)]</ref> the latter being a storehouse of information on the books and their authors.
